nd Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Pierre II de Dax was born in 1135, in France, his father, Vicomte Raymond Arnaud II de Dax Vicomte de Dax, was 30 and his mother, Etiennette de Barcelona, was 17. He had at least 1 daughter with Viscountess Beatrix de Bigorre. He died before 1190."},"et":{"1135–Bef 1190":"1135–enne 1190","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1141–Female":"1141–Surnud","1163–Female":"1163–Surnud","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1118–1165":"1118–1165","1118":"1118","1190":"1190","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","1167":"1167","1165":"1165","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1141":"1141","Bef 1190":"enne 1190","France":"Prantsusmaa","Dax, Landes, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Dax, Landes, Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1135–Bef 1190":"1135–ennen vuotta 1190","1135–1190":"1135–1190","1141–Female":"1141–Kuollut","1163–Female":"1163–Kuollut","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1118–1165":"1118–1165","1118":"1118","1190":"1190","1105":"1105","1135":"